A statement from the Nottingham East Labour Assembly on Friday said: “We wish the meetings to include everyone and be fruitful.”
For most of my eight years as a local representative of Labour in Parliament, Friday meetings were just that.
Unfortunately, today the tone of most meetings and promises of a “lighter and more measured” policy have long been forgotten if they were ever on the agenda at all.
It became increasingly obvious that different views were not tolerated in the Labour Party and that any opinion was judged on the basis of how much the party leadership liked it.
This started soon after Jeremy became a leader, while the colleagues I worked for before I thought they shared similar political views, started expecting me to turn around and take positions I would never agree with – be it on national security or the EU’s single market.
Whenever I make public statements – no matter what I say – there is a whole offensive tirade in social networks, where there is a call for a recall, a rejection of moderate politics, statements that I do not belong to the Labour Party.
It doesn't just happen to me.
In the interests of truth, I know that I have even drawn more luck than some of my colleagues, since the comments to me are at least mostly political in nature.
I can only admire the professionalism and purposefulness of those colleagues who face sexist or racist ridicule every day without being afraid of them.
One of the biggest disappointments of this era in politics is how such insults have become the norm.
Last week, Jeremy Corbyn said Labour should embrace a culture of tolerance.
The reality is that the party is no longer broad-based, and with every sign of distrust or change in the rules of choice, it becomes increasingly narrow.
In the last two years I have received many advices to calm down, not to talk so much and that then "everything will be fine".
But that’s not why I got into politics.
Ever since I joined the Labour Party 32 years ago as a student provoked by Thatcher’s government, which by its neglect led to a literal breakdown of my excellent school, I have fought for better public services for those who need them most – whether as a local councillor or as a minister.
I have never hidden my political views, including during the last election.
No one in Nottingham East could be confused in any way by my political position and my disagreement with the current leadership.
To all those who supported the proposal on Friday, I would like to say that when the state moves towards Brexit, it will harm households, businesses and the public sector, and I do not understand the desire to waste my time and energy in loyalty to the leader of the Labour Party.
But really my message is not to Nottingham Momentum, but to my constituents, whether they are members of the Labour Party or not: It is my pride to serve you and I promise that no threat of withdrawal or political expulsion will prevent me from acting in the way that I consider to be in your best interest.
Crisley Leslie is a Member of Parliament for Nottingham East
