John Edwards: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a reputation for academic excellence, continuing in 2018 with another superb presentation of the test results, which is only reinforced by individual and collective successes in the sports, art, music and other social sciences.
With up to 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Association of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to offer the best level to their students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for their further education, their chosen career and their place in a global world.
As an educational sector that can compile and implement a personal curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and desirable subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you talk to someone in a language they understand, your words will get to them.
But if you speak his own language, you touch his heart.”
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely only on the English language when we want to build relationships and trust with the peoples of other countries.
Through the results of this year’s exams, we see that languages are at the first place with the highest success for independent schools.
A total of 68% of the students who studied foreign languages achieved a high score of A.
The data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72% of the students achieved grade A in Chinese, with the same score having 72% of the students studying German, 69% of the schools French and 63% of those with Spanish.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland perceive foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will definitely need in the future.
Currently, languages as subjects of free choice by students receive the same attitude as natural-mathematical disciplines (scientific, technological, engineering and mathematical disciplines) both in the programs of independent schools and beyond them.
A survey conducted in 2014 by the UK Employment and Skills Commission showed that, because of the reasons employers find it difficult to find employees, 17% indicated insufficient language skills.
Therefore, more and more the mastery of foreign languages becomes mandatory in order to prepare young people for their future careers.
More and more job positions require the mastery of a foreign language, which makes these skills essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the chosen career, if a person mastered a foreign language, he will have a real advantage in the future, having mastered such a skill, which remains for a lifetime.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically puts the multi-lingual person one breast ahead of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 UK adult citizens in 2013, 75% did not speak a foreign language well enough to be able to practice a language, with French being the only language whose proficiency reaches a two-digit rate of 15%.
That’s why investing in language learning today is important for children now.
Learning several languages, especially those of developing economies, will provide children with a better chance of finding a good job.
In Scotland, each school will be different from the languages taught.
A number of schools will focus on more classic modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered more important to the UK in the future by 2020, such as Chinese or Japanese.
Whatever interests your child may have, there will always be enough languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers being specialists in their field.
Independent schools in Scotland are firmly committed to providing an educational environment that will prepare children and give them the skills they need to succeed in life, no matter what the future holds.
At the moment, it cannot be denied that in a global business environment languages continue to play an incredibly important role for the future of any country, which requires this to be taken into account in the education system.
And indeed, modern languages should really be considered “international communication skills”.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, along with diversity and excellent quality, to young people in Scotland.
It has to be done.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Association of Independent Schools.
