North Korea says there is "no way" to disarm unilaterally, without trust
North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions deepen mistrust of the United States and there is no way the country could unilaterally abandon its nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
At the annual general meeting of the world organization, Ri Yong-hou said that in the last year "significant measures of good will have been taken", for example, stopping nuclear and missile tests, destroying the site for nuclear tests and promises not to spread nuclear weapons and technologies.
“However, we do not see a corresponding reaction from the United States,” he said.
“Without trust in the United States, we will not believe in our own national security, and under no circumstances will there be a way to disarm unilaterally first.”
While Ree expressed North Korea’s well-known grievances about Washington’s resistance to a “staged” approach to the elimination of nuclear weapons, in which North Korea would be rewarded for taking phased measures, his statement seemed significant as it did not reject the one-sided predicate.
Ri cited a joint statement by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first summit between the U.S. president and the North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work for “nuclear disarmament of the Korean Peninsula,” and Trump gave the Sedona security guarantees.
North Korea is seeking an official end to the 1950-1953 Korean War, but the U.S. says Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also opposed calls to ease tough international sanctions against North Korea.
“The U.S. insists on ‘removing nuclear weapons first’ and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal through coercion, and even objects to ‘the declaration of an end to the war,’” Ri said.
“The notion that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a meaningless dream for those who don’t know us.
The problem, however, is that the continued sanctions deepen our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention whether a second meeting between Kim and Trump is planned, which the U.S. leader stressed at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister emphasized the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If the country on the issue of nuclear disarmament was South Korea, not the United States, the removal of nuclear weapons on the Korean peninsula would not have reached such a point.
However, Ri’s tone of speech was significantly different from the previous year when he told the UN General Assembly that targeting North Korean missiles on the U.S. mainland was inevitable after “evil president” Trump called Kim a “human-missile” of a suicide mine.
