Students at Harvard on a course for enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year causes all students to sleep more in an attempt to overcome the growing culture of “all-night” learning with the help of caffeine.
A professor found that students at the world’s number one university often don’t even think about the very basics of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Kaiser, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at the Brigham and Women’s Hospital, prepared the course he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after talking about the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At last a girl came to me and said, ‘Why are they telling me this only now, in my last year?’
She said no one ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, which is held for the first time this year, explains to students the most important thing about how good sleep habits help academic and sports achievements, as well as improving overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university has decided to introduce the course after it was found that students suffer from severe lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one part there is an image of a room in a dormitory where students click on cups of coffee, curtains, sneakers and books to explain to them the effects of caffeine and light, how sports achievements are affected by lack of sleep, as well as the importance of the bedtime routine.
Another part of the participants tells how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risks of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
Then a map of the campus with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that this will not immediately change the behavior of students.
But we believe they have a right to know – just as you have a right to know the health effects of choosing to smoke,” added Professor Kaiser.
The culture of pride in “learning all night” still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students mean sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
Ensuring adequate and quality sleep should be the “secret weapon” of students in the fight against stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he says – even in order to avoid fulfillment, as sleep deprivation puts the brain into a mode of hunger, which makes them constantly hungry.
Raymond Soe, a 19-year-old California student studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Kaiser prepare the course by taking one of his classes during his first year at Harvard.
He says his course has “opened his eyes” and inspired him to spread it throughout the campus.
It is hoped that the next step is for all graduate students to be asked to complete such a curriculum before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Kaiser recommends students to think about whether to set a bedtime and wake-up alarm and know the harmful effects of the “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting, which can upset the circadian rhythm and lead to problems with sleep.
