The inventor of the World Wide Web plans to launch a new Internet to attack Google and Facebook
The inventor of the World Wide Web, Tim Berners-Lee, has launched an initiative that aims to rival Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of the technology legend, Inrupt, is a company that builds the open source platform of Berners-Lee Solid.
Solid allows users to choose where their data is stored and which people have permission to access certain information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the intention behind Inrupt was “world domination.”
"We have to do it now," he said of the venture.
“This is a historic moment.”
The app uses Solid technology, which allows people to create their own “online personal data store” or POD.
It contains lists, to-do lists, calendar, music library, and other personal and professional tools.
It’s similar to Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack, and Spotify, which are accessible through any browser, and at the same time are all of them at the same time.
The unique thing about online storage of personal data is that the user determines who has access to what information.
The company calls it “giving authority to personal data.”
The idea for Inrupt, according to the company’s CEO John Bruce, is for the company to invest resources, processes and appropriate skills to help Solid become accessible to everyone.
The company currently consists of Burners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, several developers contracted to work on the project, and a group of volunteer programmers.
As of this week, technology developers around the world can create their own decentralized applications using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team are not talking to Facebook and Google about whether to make a complete change, or not, when all of their business models are completely updated overnight.
“We don’t want permission from them.”
In a Medium post on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that Inrupt’s mission is to provide energy for trade and the ecosystem to help protect the integrity and quality of the new network built on Solid.
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he created the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has had a strong influence on the net neutrality debate.
Despite launching Inrupt, Berners-Lee will remain the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, Web Foundation and Open Data Institute.
“I’m extremely optimistic about this new era on the internet,” Berners-Lee added.
