Germany has postponed the launch of a new warship.
The German Navy’s newest frigate was due to be commissioned in 2014 to replace the aging Cold War war warships, but that won’t happen until at least next year due to faulty systems and rising costs, local media reported.
The commissioning of Rheinland-Pfalz, the brand’s leading ship of new Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates, has been delayed until the first half of 2019, according to Die Zeit newspaper, which quotes an army spokesman.
The vessel was supposed to join the Navy in 2014, but the problems that arose after its delivery affected the fate of the ambitious project.
The four ships of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class, ordered by the fleet in 2007, will replace the obsolete frigates of the Bremen class.
It is understandable that they will have a powerful weapon, a set of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as some stealth technologies, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signals.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods – the latest frigates must be able to be used for up to two years before returning to home ports.
However, the continuous delays mean that state-of-the-art warships – which are said to allow Germany to demonstrate power beyond the ocean – will be old by the time they enter service, Die Zeit notes.
The ill-fated F125 frigate entered the headlines last year when the German fleet officially refused to put the vessel into service and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This is the first time the fleet has returned a ship to a shipbuilder after delivery.
Little is known about the reasons for the return, but German media cited a number of significant "software and hardware defects" that render the warship unusable if sent on a combat mission.
Software deficiencies are particularly important as Baden-Wuerttemberg-class vessels will be operated by a crew of about 120 sailors – only half the crew of older Bremen-class frigates.
In addition, it turned out that the ship is significantly overloaded, which reduces its efficiency and limits the ability of the naval forces to add future upgrades.
The 7000-tonne Rhineland-Palatinate is believed to be twice as heavy as the similar class of ships used by the Germans during World War II.
In addition to faulty hardware, the cost of the entire project – including crew training – also becomes a problem.
It is estimated to have reached a staggering 3.1 billion euros ($3.6 billion) out of the original 2.2 billion euros.
The problems with the latest frigates are becoming particularly important in light of recent warnings that Germany’s naval forces are shrinking.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the defence committee of the German parliament, acknowledged that the fleet was actually "depleting from ships capable of carrying out missions".
The official said the problem has become bigger over time as the old ships have been decommissioned but no new ones have been provided.
He complained that no frigate of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class could join the fleet.
The National Trust monitors the secret life of bats
A new study, conducted at a property in the Scottish mountains, aims to determine how bats use the landscape when hunting.
The hopes are that the findings will shed new light on the behavior of unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation efforts.
The study by scientists from the National Trust of Scotland will follow common bats as well as brown arrow-eared water-nighters at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed in key locations in the estate to track the activities of the bats during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using hand-held detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of callous sounds of bats, as well as what types they emit.
Then a map of the habitat and a report will be prepared to create a detailed landscape picture of their behavior.
Rob Duar, Nature Conservation Advisor for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by any species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as the creation of meadows, as well as the best way to maintain forest areas for bats and other related species.
The populations of bats in Scotland and the UK as a whole have declined significantly over the past century.
They are at risk from construction activities that affect their shelters and lead to habitat loss.
There may be a risk to populations from wind turbines and lighting, aircraft and some chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, because of their hunting habits at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use an advanced echolocation technique to detect insects and obstacles along their flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
The Trust has trained experts who conduct regular surveys, inspections of shelters and sometimes rescue operations.
The organisation has even created Scotland’s first and only special bat reserve at the Threeave estate in the Dumfries and Galway area, home to eight of Scotland’s ten bat species.
The estate’s manager, David Thompson, says it’s an ideal territory for them.
“Here at Threeave, we have a great field for bats,” he said.
“We have old buildings, a lot of mature trees and a completed suitable habitat.
But there are many more things about bats that are not known, so the work we do here and in other properties will help us better understand what they need to thrive.”
He stressed that it is important to check for the presence of bats before carrying out property maintenance activities, since it is possible to unintentionally destroy one shelter to kill up to 400 female and young bats, as well as destroy the entire local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass, disturb or destroy their shelters.
Elizabeth Ferrel, a Scottish employee at the Bat Protection Trust, encouraged the public to help.
She said: “I still have a lot to learn about our bats and a lot of our animal species, because we just don’t know what’s going on with their populations.”
