New for the red tide: Concentrations decrease in Pinelas, Manotti and Sarasota
The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Committee shows a fundamental reduction in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the Committee, there are reports of conditions for curtailment of growth in the areas of the districts of Pinelas, Manotti, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier – this shows a decrease in concentrations.
The watersheds with excessive blooming of the red tide extend approximately 130 miles along the coast, from the northern district of Pinelas to the southern district of Lee.
Algal deposits can be seen 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but are less than they were last week.
A red tide is also seen in Pasco County.
Over the past week, there have been reports of moderate concentrations in the coastal zone or a little further inland in the county of Pinelas, low to high concentrations in the county of Hillsborough, high concentrations in the county of Manoti, high concentrations in the county of Pinelas, or high concentrations in the county of Pinelas.
Inflammation of the airways in Pinelas, Manotti, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties continues to be reported.
There have been no reports of respiratory infections in Northwestern Florida in the past week.
